<Page title="attr-toggle">
  <Block>
    <p>The <strong>attr-toggle</strong> property is used to toggle a boolean attribute. To set an attribute that contains a value, use the <Attr /> property instead.</p>
    <p>attr-toggle is a <MultiBinding />, which means you can toggle multiple boolean attributes on the same element.</p>
    <p>The <strong>first value</strong> is the attribute name to be toggled and the <strong>second value</strong> is the condition on which the attribute should be added or removed.</p>
  </Block>
  <Block>
    <p>A boolean attribute is one where the attribute either exists, with an empty string value, or does not exist, on an element. An example is the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Attributes/disabled">disabled</a> attribute commonly used on form elements.</p>
    <p>In this example, the disabled attribute is being toggled on a button when a form is in a state where it cannot be submitted.</p>
    <Code slot="code" lang="css" code={`
form .submit {
  attr-toggle: disabled var(--invalid);
}
`} />
  </Block>
</Page>